{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516960"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:48:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:48:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12735"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12735"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.06,0.01,0.43,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113156"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5190"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95183"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43893"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46735"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113156"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two day history of upper abdominal pain and the recent passage of dark, sticky and offensive smelling stools. There has been no nausea, vomiting nor diarrhoea. His history includes hypertension, osteoarthritis of the knees, and a previous ischaemic stroke 1 year ago. The only medications he takes are enalapril and aspirin. He is a non-smoker and non-drinker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 155/90 mmHg, pulse 70/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 20/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 97% on room air. He has epigastric tenderness without guarding and no abdominal distension. Digital rectal examination confirms the presence of melaena stool. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 102 g/L (135-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaematocrit: 0.30 (0.38-0.50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPLT: 190 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea: 10.2 mmol/L (2.5-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECr: 93 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin: 6 \u00b5mol/L (0-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 40 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV pantoprazole","IV octreotide","Platelet transfusion","Endoscopy","CT abdomen/pelvis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical scenario is most consistent with upper gastrointestinal bleeding. The patient\u0027s aspirin use, epigastric pain, melaena, anaemia and elevated urea:creatinine ratio suggest an upper gastrointestinal source of bleeding, most likely an aspirin-associated peptic ulcer. This patient is in the Emergency Department, is haemodynamically stable and will require both acid suppression and an endoscopy. The priority should be to start acid suppression therapy whilst awaiting the endoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore,\u003Cstrong\u003E IV pantoprazole \u003C/strong\u003Eis the next recommended step to suppress acid secretion and promote ulcer healing while awaiting confirmatory endoscopy to both diagnose and potentially treat the source of bleeding. Pantoprazole is a proton pump inhibitor that inhibits gastric acid secretion and can help promote healing of ulcers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOctreotide\u003C/strong\u003E is a somatostatin analogue that can reduce splanchnic blood flow, which can help control bleeding. It is commonly used in the management of upper gastrointestinal bleeding associated with oesophageal varices. In this case, IV octreotide is not indicated, as the patient has no signs of liver disease to suggest oesophageal varices as the cause of bleeding. Instead, his aspirin use without acid-suppression therapy has likely led to a peptic ulcer\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E platelet transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E will not reverse the effect aspirin has had on platelets. Note that despite his normal platelet level, his platelets are dysfunctional due to aspirin use. Platelet transfusion is indicated for patients with low platelet counts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful imaging modality in certain situations, such as suspected diverticular bleeding or lower GI bleeding. However, in this case, the clinical presentation and absence of signs suggestive of lower GI bleeding indicate an upper GI bleed. Therefore, a CT scan of the abdomen/pelvis is not the initial investigation of choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is considered the gold standard in diagnosis and management of upper gastrointestinal haemorrhage, but in cases such as this, where there is haemodynamic stability, it is not the initial step to be taken. Endoscopy not only helps determine the cause of the bleeding, such as gastric or duodenal ulcers, erosive gastritis, or oesophageal varices, but also allows for potential interventions to control the bleeding, such as cauterisation, injection therapy, or mechanical clipping.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A proton pump inhibitor should be started promptly in cases of upper gastrointestinal haemorrhage where peptic ulcer disease is thought to be the underlying problem."],"references":["Antunes C, Copelin II EL. Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding. [Updated 2022 Jul 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95183"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12735"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95183"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T08:26:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T08:26:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5190"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113156"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"positi